          "title": "The architecture of completion — twelves, cubes, and precious stones",
          "body": "The architectural section (vv. 12-21) is dense with deliberate numerology. The city has twelve gates, twelve angels at the gates, twelve foundations, twelve apostles' names, twelve tribes' names. It is measured at 12,000 stadia (12 × 1000), with walls 144 cubits (12 × 12) thick. The shape is a perfect cube — the same proportions as the Holy of Holies in Solomon's temple (1 Kings 6:20, a twenty-cubit cube). The whole redeemed community now lives in the inner sanctum; what was once a once-a-year visit by one man is now eternal residence for all. The twelve foundation stones (vv. 19-20) parallel the twelve stones on the high priest's breastplate (Exodus 28:17-20) representing the tribes — but the stones in Revelation 21 belong to the *apostles*, weaving Israel and the church into one priestly community. Every architectural detail testifies that the consummation is structurally complete, covenantally inclusive, and liturgically saturated."
